title: For Sale:  Pre-Ban Saiga-12: RARE Kushnapup AND Battle Conversion BOTH
postcontent:
This gun was originally converted from a full-length Saiga-12 into a standard combat shotgun. It is rare for several reasons: 

1.) It was made by Izhmash and imported prior to the ban; lots of guns look like these, but this is the real deal from the factory in Izhevsk. Do your homework, and you'll find that these are the best AK pattern shotguns ever made.

2.) It was converted in the USA, with top-of-the-line parts and fully reworked machanicals; broken in properly, with adjustable gas tuned perfectly for high and low brass by a friend who is a Russian veteran. I wanted a gun I could bet my life on, and this is it. It also shoots BOTH 2 3/4" AND 3" magnum slugs without complaint.

3.) No matter what anyone tells you, a short pull on one of these is not a good thing. These guns are just far tool powerful. Ridiculous, frankly, in rapid fire – unless you are facing down a rhino for some reason. Unlike most conversions or imitators that came afterward, this gun has the trigger in the stock position. That's important, because you can't use it as a Kushnapup (and shorten it beyond any SBR) with a relocated trigger.

3a.) That means it can be a standard AK-pattern combat shotgun, OR a Kushnapup bullpup WHENEVER YOU LIKE. The conversion takes just a few minutes because the tangs on the rear trunnion have never been cut; a serious rarity for Kushnapups. That makes it easy to reconfigure as you like. All parts for BOTH configurations are included. 

4.) It is priced to move. The Kushnapup alone with some of these upgrades is listed on Gunbroker for 2500.00. Unfortunately, this is a lean time and it feels silly to have so many guns, frankly. This is one of my favorite weapons, but I can only shoot so many at one time, and I don't have room for another shotgun. The gun is used but in great condition and with minimal wear. The pictures aren't very good, but I'm at work. The gun looks fantastic.

5. Some of you may currently have undead infestations, and may be dealing with a living room full of zombies. This will solve your problem lickety split. These guns are legendary for a reason. Personally, I have never owned a gun that came even close in terms of sheer destructive power, or a shotgun that was as accurate at longer distances. Below is a list of what comes with it.

- upgraded BCG
- upgraded extractor
- upgraded barrel w/ thread
- adjustable gas
- Tapco trigger tuned for minimum takeup
- Tapco release
- black cerakote
- screw-on muzzle shroud
- screw on sharktooth brake
- Kushnapup stock set w/ all parts (or)
- pistol grip
- Tapco adjustable stock
- Monstrum quad rail
- foregrip
- S&W LE Flashlight w/ Picatinny mount
- huge sling loop
- black paracord shotgun sling w/ HK hooks
- 3x 5rd magazines
- 2x 10 rd magazines
- 1x 20 rd drum
- cleaning kit
- original manual
- 25 rds 2 3/4" slug
- molle shell pouch
- TRUGLO open red dot
- locking TSA hardshell case* w/ wheels

 *(big enough to carry the gun and parts for both conversions)

Price is firm, no trades. I will only sell through FFL or to PA resident w/ valid state ID. No tire kickers or trolls, please. If you have the cash and want the gun, I will send you additional closeups that show it all clean and shiny. You know. The way weapons never are if you actually use them. My guess is that if you are in the market for one of these, you're smart enough to figure that part out. You will never see a truly legit one of these for less, I promise.

Thanks for looking. Feel free to text me at REDACTED.

The bolt face is good to go and free from any chips or cracks and the gas rings are new. The gas key is properly staked to the carrier and the receiver has correct "M4" cuts.

title: For Sale/Trade:  CZ-45 6.35 Browning /25 AUTO aka Vzor 45 WTT/WTS
postcontent:
Description:  CZ45 Vzor W/Extras MUST SEE !!!!  The Vzor 45, commonly known as CZ 45 is a compact blowback operated semi-automatic pistol chambered in .25 ACP . It was made in Czechoslovakia and later in the Czech Republic . Derived from the CZ-36 following World War II, the CZ-45 is currently manufactured by ÄŒeská zbrojovka Uherský Brod as the CZ-92.   In 1945 the CZ-36 was redesigned by Jan Kratochvil to make it easier (hence cheaper) to manufacture and became the Vzor 45 (model 1945) but is generally known as CZ-45. The safety lever which had sometimes appeared on the CZ-36 was eliminated (though a few early model 45s were manufactured with a safety lever). The changes included the addition of a side plate to simplify assembly and a magazine safety. The CZ-36 had a connector from the trigger to the hammer that ran on the left side of the magazine, whereas the CZ-45 has a Browning style stirrup-shaped connector that runs on both sides of the magazine.   The overall design of the receiver, slide, guide rod, and recoil spring are very similar to the earlier Browning .25 design. The barrel mount is also like the Browning, with a single lug that rotates into a slot in the frame. The trigger pivots on a pin.   When the trigger is activated and the hammer is down, the connector is pulled forward, rotating the hammer backward into cocked position. When the hammer reaches full cock, it is freed to fall and strike the firing pin , which ignites the cartridge. The hammer is not cocked by the slide--technically speaking, this is a self-loading repeating pistol, not an automatic or semi-automatic. Other than the heavy double-action trigger pull, the only safety mechanism is the magazine safety. When the magazine is inserted, it moves a bar which allows the connector to engage the sear. When the magazine is removed from the gun, the bar disconnects the trigger from the sear.   Disassembly is similar to the Browning. Remove the magazine and make sure the chamber is empty. Draw the slide back about 1 centimeter and rotate the barrel clockwise a quarter-turn. Remove the barrel and slide forward off the receiver. Other than the guide rod and recoil spring, there are no small parts that come loose.   The CZ-45 holds 8 rounds in the magazine and has a simple groove down the top of the slide for sighting. Its great merits are its simplicity and reliability, ease of field-stripping, and accuracy--despite its primitive sighting groove and double action only trigger.    In 1992 the gun was slightly redesigned, given a magazine release behind the trigger and a futuristic grip, and is now sold as the CZ-92. Unfortunately, due to the Gun Control Act of 1968, the gun can no longer be imported into the U.S., as it is too small. After the GCA blocked further importation, US Manufacturer Intratec started producing a near-exact clone called the Protec, though the build quality is somewhat lower.   CZ-45's are somewhat rare in the US resale market and go for about $250 in good condition and up to $750 in mint condition. CZ-92's are virtually non-existing in the US and go for higher prices, despite the limited applications of the .25 ACP as a self-defense round.   The CZ Custom Shop in the United States is planning to produce a limited run of US-made CZ 92's. A prototype was shown at the 2011 SHOT Show. CZ Custom aims to have the US-made CZ-92 included in the CZ Catalog at the 2012 SHOT Show. It is not confirmed if the chambering will remain .25ACP or possibly switch to .32 or .380.  


The modern successors to the Model CZ-45 are the:


Seecamp .25 and ,32


North American Arms .32 and .380,


&
